JODY ADAMS: So temperature and
time, obviously, are very important.

00:53:20.260 --> 00:53:24.740
But this little gizmo, if you
want to make your own yogurt,

00:53:24.740 --> 00:53:30.700
if you want to start being super healthy
and without being obnoxious about it,

00:53:30.700 --> 00:53:34.610
just in a good way, with great flavor.

00:53:34.610 --> 00:53:38.270
This is a really good
little machine to have.

00:53:38.270 --> 00:53:39.490
Can you see it?

00:53:43.140 --> 00:53:47.110
So you have a whole
fermentation program right here.

00:53:47.110 --> 00:53:48.000
Without even trying.

00:53:55.430 --> 00:53:57.030
I think the pickles are so exciting.

00:53:57.030 --> 00:54:01.680
And I remember, when I was a
kid, there was a sandwich shop

00:54:01.680 --> 00:54:06.200
and it was actually-- does everybody
know who Wiley Dufresne is?

00:54:06.200 --> 00:54:11.590
So his father had a sandwich shop called
Joe's in Providence, where I grew up.

00:54:11.590 --> 00:54:14.890
He went to RISD and he opened up first
a sandwich shop called Joe's, and

00:54:14.890 --> 00:54:18.430
a restaurant called Joe's upstairs,
which was a very cool place.

00:54:18.430 --> 00:54:22.490
And in the middle of the
sandwich shop was a barrel.

00:54:22.490 --> 00:54:24.970
And in the barrel were pickles.

00:54:24.970 --> 00:54:27.050
And in my memories,
they were just floating.

00:54:27.050 --> 00:54:29.610
I don't think we stuck our hands in.

00:54:29.610 --> 00:54:33.030
But I remember they must have the
plastic top on them, or something.

00:54:33.030 --> 00:54:35.910
Because I can't imagine that
you just kind of walked in

00:54:35.910 --> 00:54:37.180
and looked at the pickles.

00:54:37.180 --> 00:54:39.610
But they were just
floating around in there.

00:54:39.610 --> 00:54:43.320
And that's what they were, is this.

00:54:43.320 --> 00:54:45.700
Did anybody go to Joe's?

00:54:45.700 --> 00:54:47.408
Did you go to Joe's?

00:54:47.408 --> 00:54:48.490
It's Jeff's now.

00:54:48.490 --> 00:54:49.860
It's not nearly as good.

00:54:49.860 --> 00:54:50.615
It's really dirty.

00:55:01.450 --> 00:55:04.780
I hope I didn't screw
up the pickles too.

00:55:04.780 --> 00:55:06.120
No, you keep it at 70 degrees.

00:55:06.120 --> 00:55:06.620
OK.

00:55:09.180 --> 00:55:13.570
As I said, for the pickles, there's
naturally occurring bacteria

00:55:13.570 --> 00:55:15.260
on the outside of the pickles.

00:55:15.260 --> 00:55:18.340
They interact with the sugars.

00:55:18.340 --> 00:55:22.720
They like being in a salt brine
at a certain temperature, which

00:55:22.720 --> 00:55:24.450
is about 70 degrees.

00:55:24.450 --> 00:55:26.320
And they will start fermenting.

00:55:26.320 --> 00:55:30.280
And what everybody says, when
you're reading about them,

00:55:30.280 --> 00:55:32.610
is taste, taste, taste.

00:55:32.610 --> 00:55:38.180
And when they get to a point that
you like, put them in the fridge.

00:55:38.180 --> 00:55:40.930
Keep a cover over them.

00:55:40.930 --> 00:55:43.840
You want to cover them up completely,
because they're fermenting

00:55:43.840 --> 00:55:49.610
and there's gas coming off, and they
could pop the top off something.

00:55:49.610 --> 00:55:51.430
Put a cheesecloth over the top.

00:55:51.430 --> 00:55:52.910
Just put them on your counter.

00:55:52.910 --> 00:55:54.530
Don't put them in direct sunlight.

00:55:54.530 --> 00:55:57.280
And just let them hang out.

00:55:57.280 --> 00:56:03.970
You want them to be in something with
a fairly wide top, not super narrow,

00:56:03.970 --> 00:56:08.490
because they pretty much guarantee
they're going to develop mold.

00:56:08.490 --> 00:56:11.300
And you just skim that mold off.

00:56:11.300 --> 00:56:12.860
And be diligent about that.

00:56:12.860 --> 00:56:14.570
I had two going at the same time.

00:56:14.570 --> 00:56:18.490
I had this one and I had another
one that was more this size,

00:56:18.490 --> 00:56:22.050
and I ignored the small one, and
the mold got into the pickle flavor.

00:56:22.050 --> 00:56:23.590
So I had to dump them out.

00:56:23.590 --> 00:56:27.740
But the other, this one,
I just kept skimming.

00:56:27.740 --> 00:56:30.680
Are you eating pickles?

00:56:30.680 --> 00:56:33.010
Did you like the pickles?

00:56:33.010 --> 00:56:34.990
You wouldn't say no anyway.

00:56:34.990 --> 00:56:36.910
You could say no once I leave.

00:56:36.910 --> 00:56:38.260
Yes?

00:56:38.260 --> 00:56:39.010
How long?

00:56:39.010 --> 00:56:42.860
They took about 10 days before
I put them in the fridge.

00:56:46.700 --> 00:56:51.030
And that salt solution
was three tablespoons

00:56:51.030 --> 00:56:59.070
per quart, which is, I
think, about 5% solution.

00:56:59.070 --> 00:57:03.057
You can work with a lower
salt solution if you want,

00:57:03.057 --> 00:57:04.640
if you don't want them quite as salty.

00:57:04.640 --> 00:57:05.575
It'll take longer.

00:57:11.360 --> 00:57:14.179
So fermentation is preservation.

00:57:14.179 --> 00:57:15.470
That's what we've talked about.

00:57:15.470 --> 00:57:17.029
We've talked about flavor.

00:57:17.029 --> 00:57:18.570
The flavor of those pickles is great.

00:57:18.570 --> 00:57:20.610
We add pickles to everything.

00:57:20.610 --> 00:57:23.380
We add them as accents, garnishes.

00:57:23.380 --> 00:57:25.700
Think about adding olives and capers.

00:57:25.700 --> 00:57:28.900
All of those things that
have big, bold flavors.

00:57:28.900 --> 00:57:35.590
That's what give food
its depth, and it's

00:57:35.590 --> 00:57:38.800
what gives food it's
memory quality for you.

00:57:38.800 --> 00:57:41.380
You're going to remember that
pickle much longer than you're

00:57:41.380 --> 00:57:42.760
going to remember the cucumber.

00:57:42.760 --> 00:57:46.240
And it's going to stay-- the
flavor's going to stay in your mouth

00:57:46.240 --> 00:57:48.280
much longer than a cucumber.

00:57:48.280 --> 00:57:52.590
So it's important to have
those kinds of flavors in food.

00:57:52.590 --> 00:57:56.860
And if you don't have them,
then food is really boring.

00:58:00.430 --> 00:58:04.510
Fermenting is also,
obviously, about preservation

00:58:04.510 --> 00:58:13.640
and preserving milk with yogurt,
cucumbers to pickles, and bread.

00:58:13.640 --> 00:58:15.380
Sourdough bread .

00:58:15.380 --> 00:58:19.140
It's also very healthy.

00:58:19.140 --> 00:58:24.990
As we talked about in sourdoughs,
the pre-digested culture--

00:58:24.990 --> 00:58:28.530
oh, no, we didn't talk about this,
but the pre-digested culture of bread

00:58:28.530 --> 00:58:34.070
reduces the presence of gluten,
making it easier for us to digest.

00:58:34.070 --> 00:58:40.450
So because the bacteria
has started breaking down,

00:58:40.450 --> 00:58:43.070
more of the sugars in
the gluten, it's easier

00:58:43.070 --> 00:58:46.570
to digest than a non-sourdough bread.

00:58:46.570 --> 00:58:51.340
It also lasts longer.

00:58:51.340 --> 00:58:53.930
Yogurt, is the same thing
is true, as I talked about.

00:58:53.930 --> 00:58:57.740
And pickles, there are also
good things that happen,

00:58:57.740 --> 00:59:00.147
like vitamin B, that come into play.

00:59:03.547 --> 00:59:05.880
Fermentation is also a really
good thing for the planet.

00:59:05.880 --> 00:59:11.550
I met a woman the other day who
is the CEO of a company that has,

00:59:11.550 --> 00:59:14.340
she called them, anaerobic digesters.

00:59:14.340 --> 00:59:19.490
And they're these huge
machines to collect waste.

00:59:19.490 --> 00:59:20.800
Organic waste.

00:59:20.800 --> 00:59:26.300
And they're digested, and it produces
methane gas that's used as fuel

00:59:26.300 --> 00:59:29.470
and produces fertilizer.

00:59:29.470 --> 00:59:36.880
And this is the kind of process that we
should be supporting and looking for,

00:59:36.880 --> 00:59:38.960
because we need different
kinds of energy.

00:59:41.860 --> 00:59:46.090
So I think we need to
stop the war on microbes.

00:59:46.090 --> 00:59:49.260
Stop sanitizing so much.

00:59:49.260 --> 00:59:50.490
We are microbes.

00:59:50.490 --> 00:59:54.950
We are covered with them, inside and
out, and we need to remain that way.

00:59:54.950 --> 01:00:04.030
They provide a protection against
bad microbes who want to attack us.

01:00:04.030 --> 01:00:11.030
And without them, we're vulnerable
to colds, infections, and allergies.

01:00:11.030 --> 01:00:15.097
I think allergies is a big one that
people are really interested in.

01:00:18.760 --> 01:00:23.530
So when I started as
a cook 30 years ago,

01:00:23.530 --> 01:00:28.740
flavor was something that
we found in big fats, lots

01:00:28.740 --> 01:00:32.240
of meat, butter and cream.

01:00:32.240 --> 01:00:41.590
And over the years, as I've aged
and my interest in food has shifted,

01:00:41.590 --> 01:00:44.070
I've become much more
interested in foods that have

01:00:44.070 --> 01:00:46.680
big flavors coming from somewhere else.

01:00:46.680 --> 01:00:53.430
In this case, with fermented foods
that really makes food, as I said,

01:00:53.430 --> 01:00:55.200
much, much more interesting.

01:00:55.200 --> 01:00:56.700
Much more fun to play with.

01:00:56.700 --> 01:01:02.595
And really fun to watch what
fermentation is doing in our kitchens.

01:01:05.320 --> 01:01:06.510
Look for flavor.

01:01:06.510 --> 01:01:11.990
Look for it in the right places,
where it really makes a difference,

01:01:11.990 --> 01:01:15.450
and brings memories,
and makes you feel good,

01:01:15.450 --> 01:01:20.400
and you can be
experimental and have fun.

01:01:20.400 --> 01:01:21.950
Thank you.

